define i8 @test_undef_condition_bug(i8 %x, i8 %y) {
  %cond = icmp eq i8 undef, 0
  %val = add i8 %x, 1
  %sel = select i1 %cond, i8 %val, i8 %y
  ret i8 %sel
}
```", "opt -S -passes=instcombine"], "thoughts": "## Bug Triggering Analysis\nThe test case exposes a bug in the new optimization that simplifies select arms based on KnownBits implied by the condition. When the condition contains `undef` (e.g., `icmp eq i8 undef, 0`), the optimization incorrectly assumes the condition is true and folds the select to always return the true arm. This is incorrect because `undef` means the condition could be either true or false, so the select could return either arm.\n\nSpecifically:\n- Original: `select i1 (icmp eq i8 undef, 0), i8 (add i8 %x, 1), i8 %y`\n- When `%x=5, %y=10`, the original could return either `6` (if undef==0) or `10` (if undef!=0)\n- Transformed: Always returns `6` (the true arm)\n- This is incorrect because undef condition means either arm could be chosen\n\n## Fix Weakness Analysis\nThe fix has a fundamental weakness: it doesn't handle undef/poison values in conditions correctly. The commit message mentions \"would also have to limit to non-undef conditions\" for future generalization, but the current implementation doesn't check for undef conditions. The `findValuesAffectedByCondition` and `computeKnownBitsFromCond` functions propagate known bits from undef conditions as if they were concrete values, leading to incorrect constant folding.\n\nThe bug reveals that the optimization needs to:\n1. Check if the condition contains undef/poison before applying the optimization\n2. Either skip the optimization or handle undef conservatively (don't propagate known bits from undef)\n3. The current implementation incorrectly assumes conditions are concrete when they contain undef"}

